{"title_page": "Camp Down", "text_new": "[[File:Farmland and pylon, Woodford - geograph.org.uk - 489472.jpg|thumb|A field of oilseed rape above Camp Down]]\n'''Camp Down''' ({{gbmapping|SU120338}}) is a {{convert|7.3|hectare|adj=on}} [[biological Site of Special Scientific Interest]] in [[Wiltshire]] in [[South West England]]. It was [[SSSI notification|designated]] as such in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/SiteDetail.aspx?SiteCode=S1002448&SiteName=camp%20down&countyCode=&responsiblePerson=&SeaArea=&IFCAArea=|title=Camp Down SSSI|work=Natural England Designated Sites View|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Location ==\nThe area overlooks the valley of the [[River Avon, Hampshire|River Avon]], northwest of [[Salisbury]].<ref name=sssi/> It lies east of the [[A360 road]], which runs from Salisbury to [[Devizes]] via [[Stonehenge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/51%C2%B006'12.2%22N+1%C2%B049'48.0%22W/@51.1073645,-1.83587,2377m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x0!8m2!3d51.103378!4d-1.829987?hl=en|title=Camp Down|work=Google Maps|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Environment== \nThe down has a [[chalk grassland]] that has been well grazed and contains numerous plants, which is typical of grass sites in South Wilshire. Over 20 types of grasses and [[sedge]]s have been recorded at Camp Down, including [[Festuca rubra|red fescue]], [[Bromus erectus|upright brome]], [[Briza media|quaking-grass]], [[Koeleria macrantha|crested hair-grass]] and [[Carex flacca|glaucous sedge]]. The turf contains a variety of herbs, including [[Cirsium acaule|dwarf thistle]] and [[Leucanthemum vulgare|ox-eye daisy]]. There are a significant number of [[orchid]]s, particularly ''[[Gymnadenia conopsea]]''.<ref name=sssi>{{cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1002448.pdf|title=Camp Down : Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI) notified under Section 28 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981|work=Salisbury District Council|year=1987|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of young [[sycamore]] trees on the site, alongside patches of scrub and scattered bushes. The environment of chalk grassland mixed with scattered scrub means Camp Down is frequented to a number of types of birds and insects. Historical records show there were several types of [[plant bug]] and beetle fauna on the site.<ref name=sssi/>\n\nCamp Down has seen problems with [[badger]]s who are a prominent carrier of [[tuberculosis]]. In 2019, Nautral England reported that the government would grant a licence for [[badger culling]] on the site in the interests of preserving the environment. The action has been controversial, and criticised by the [[Badger Trust]] as unnecessarily cruel.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.spirefm.co.uk/news/local-news/2951398/badger-culling-to-take-place-in-parts-of-wiltshire/|title=Badger culling to take place in parts of Wiltshire|work=Spire FM|date=12 September 2019|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060813070641/http://www.english-nature.org.uk/ English Nature website] (SSSI information)\n\n{{SSSIs Wilts biological}}\n{{coord|51.10338|N|1.82999|W|region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(SU120338)|display=title}}<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest notified in 1965]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Farmland and pylon, Woodford - geograph.org.uk - 489472.jpg|thumb|A field of oilseed rape above Camp Down]]\n'''Camp Down''' ({{gbmapping|SU120338}}) is a {{convert|7.3|hectare|adj=on}} [[biological Site of Special Scientific Interest]] in [[Wiltshire]] in [[South West England]]. It was [[SSSI notification|designated]] as such in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/SiteDetail.aspx?SiteCode=S1002448&SiteName=camp%20down&countyCode=&responsiblePerson=&SeaArea=&IFCAArea=|title=Camp Down SSSI|work=Natural England Designated Sites View|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Location ==\nThe area overlooks the valley of the [[River Avon, Hampshire|River Avon]], northwest of [[Salisbury]].<ref name=sssi/> It lies east of the [[A360 road]], which runs from Salisbury to [[Devizes]] via [[Stonehenge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/51%C2%B006'12.2%22N+1%C2%B049'48.0%22W/@51.1073645,-1.83587,2377m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x0!8m2!3d51.103378!4d-1.829987?hl=en|title=Camp Down|work=Google Maps|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Environment== \nThe down has a [[chalk grassland]] that has been well grazed and contains numerous plants, which is typical of grass sites in South Wilshire. Over 20 types of grasses and [[sedge]]s have been recorded at Camp Down, including [[Festuca rubra|red fescue]], [[Bromus erectus|upright brome]], [[Briza media|quaking-grass]], [[Koeleria macrantha|crested hair-grass]] and [[Carex flacca|glaucous sedge]]. The turf contains a varity of herbs, including [[Cirsium acaule|dwarf thistle]] and [[Leucanthemum vulgare|ox-eye daisy]]. There are a significant number of [[orchid]]s, particularly ''[[Gymnadenia conopsea]]''.<ref name=sssi>{{cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1002448.pdf|title=Camp Down : Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI) notified under Section 28 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981|work=Salisbury District Council|year=1987|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of young [[sycamore]] trees on the site, alongside patches of scrub and scattered bushes. The environment of chalk grassland mixed with scattered scrub means Camp Down is frequented to a number of types of birds and insects. Historical records show there were several types of [[plant bug]] and beetle fauna on the site. <ref name=sssi/>\n\nCamp Down has seen problems with [[badger]]s who are a prominent carrier of [[tuberculosis]]. In 2019, Nautral England reported that the government would grant a licence for [[badger culling]] on the site in the interests of preserving the environment. The action has been controversial, and criticised by the [[Badger Trust]] as unnecessarily cruel.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.spirefm.co.uk/news/local-news/2951398/badger-culling-to-take-place-in-parts-of-wiltshire/|title=Badger culling to take place in parts of Wiltshire|work=Spire FM|date=12 September 2019|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060813070641/http://www.english-nature.org.uk/ English Nature website] (SSSI information)\n\n{{SSSIs Wilts biological}}\n{{coord|51.10338|N|1.82999|W|region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(SU120338)|display=title}}<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest notified in 1965]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEnvironment:clean up,typo(s) fixed: varity \u2192 variety", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camp_Down"}
